In [11]:
#Create label encoder for feature with less than or equal to 2  unique values
#In our case, this will be only gender column with 2 unique values ['male','female']

#Create a label encoder object
le = LabelEncoder()
# Label Encoding will be used for columns with 2 or less unique values
le_count = 0

for col in df.columns[1:]:
    if df[col].dtype == 'object':
        #print(col)
        if len(list(df[col].unique())) <= 2:
            le.fit(df[col])
            df[col] = le.transform(df[col])
            le_count += 1
            
print('{} columns were label encoded.'.format(le_count))

1 columns were label encoded.

In [14]:
#K means is distance based algorithm and the difference of magnitude could create problem. So, lets's scale the features.
scaler = StandardScaler()

data_scaled = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(df))
data_scaled.columns = df.columns.values
data_scaled.index = df.index.values

K-Means Clustering¶

In [15]:
# defining the kmeans function with initialization as k-means++
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2, init='k-means++')

# fitting the k means algorithm on scaled data
kmeans.fit(data_scaled)
Out[15]:
KMeans(n_clusters=2)
In [16]:
# inertia on the fitted data
kmeans.inertia_
Out[16]:
642473.464180227

So, when we initialize the k means algorithm by 2 clusters or 2 centroids, we got the inertia of 64247 which seems pretty high. We can find better inertia (less) by optimizing k selection. We expect to see decreasing inertia when we increase the k number. However,we also have overfitting issue in this case. To select the best k we can use the elbow plot which can be seen below.

In [17]:
# fitting multiple k-means algorithms and storing the values in an empty list
SSE = []
for cluster in range(1,20):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_jobs = -1, n_clusters = cluster, init='k-means++')
    kmeans.fit(data_scaled)
    SSE.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# converting the results into a dataframe and plotting them
frame = pd.DataFrame({'Cluster':range(1,20), 'SSE':SSE})
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
plt.plot(frame['Cluster'], frame['SSE'], marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
Out[17]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Inertia')

The elbows are : [ 2.5 , 6 , 16 ]

Let's choose the k value as 6 in our case.

In [20]:
# k means
data_scaled2=data_scaled.copy()
data_scaled2['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(data_scaled2[['age', 'tot_bill']])
# get centroids
centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_
cen_x = [i[0] for i in centroids] 
cen_y = [i[1] for i in centroids]
## add to df
data_scaled2['cen_x'] = data_scaled2.cluster.map({0:cen_x[0], 1:cen_x[1], 2:cen_x[2],3:cen_x[3], 4:cen_x[4], 5:cen_x[5]})
data_scaled2['cen_y'] = data_scaled2.cluster.map({0:cen_y[0], 1:cen_y[1], 2:cen_y[2],3:cen_y[3], 4:cen_y[4], 5:cen_y[5]})
# define and map colors
colors = ['#DF2020', '#81DF20', '#2095DF','#FFFF66','#000066','#996633']
data_scaled2['c'] = data_scaled2.cluster.map({0:colors[0], 1:colors[1], 2:colors[2],3:colors[3], 4:colors[4], 5:colors[5]})

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [22]:
#Visualize the dendogram for deciding the number of clusters for this problem
X = data_scaled.iloc[0:1000, :].values
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))  
plt.title("Dendrograms")  
dend = shc.dendrogram(shc.linkage(X, method='ward'))

We can observe that the vertical line with maximum distance occurs for cluster sizes 3 and 9. We can visualize this by selecting thereshold of 50 and 25 and cut the dendogram according to these values:

In [23]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))  
plt.title("Dendrograms")  
dend = shc.dendrogram(shc.linkage(X, method='ward'))
plt.axhline(y=50, color='r', linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=25, color='r', linestyle='--')
Out[23]:
<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1cca574e0d0>

As we can see from the above red dashed lines, there is strong possiblity that cluster size of 3 and 9 wil give us better calssification results than other cluster sizes. As cluster size 3 seems larger in vertical than cluster size of 9, we will choose the cluster size as 3 fro agglomerative clustering.

In [26]:
n_clusters = max(cluster.labels_)+1
colors = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, n_clusters))
cluster_labels = list(range(0, n_clusters))

# Create a figure of size 6 inches by 4 inches.
plt.figure(figsize=(16,14))

for color, label in zip(colors, cluster_labels):
    subset = dfhiear[dfhiear.cluster_ == label]
    plt.scatter(subset.age, subset.tot_bill, s= subset.tot_bytes, c=color, label='cluster'+str(label),alpha=0.5)

    
plt.legend()
plt.title('Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Total Bill')

#Encode units to one hot encoding as we need that type of input for apriori and association rules
#Each number larger than 0 will be converted to 1, otherwise 0.

def encode_units(x):
    if x <= 0:
        return 0
    if x >= 1:
        return 1

basket_sets = basket.applymap(encode_units)
In [39]:
